# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1936-world-series
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1936-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The **1883 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through September 30, 1883.
[src:1936-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] It was the second season for the American Association (AA) and eighth season for the National League (NL).
[src:1936-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Athletics won the AA pennant, while the Boston Beaneaters won the NL pennant.
[src:1936-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] There was no postseason, although there was a canceled exhibition series between the two pennant winners.
[src:1936-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the season, the Troy Trojans and Worcester Worcesters of the National League folded.
[src:1936-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] In its place, the league enfranchised two teams: the New York Gothams and Philadelphia Quakers (today's San Francisco Giants and Philadelphia Phillies).
[src:1936-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] It was decided that the six-team American Association would expand to eight teams and saw the minor league New York Metropolitans join and the enfranchisement of the Columbus Buckeyes.
[src:1936-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the season, the Boston Red Caps and St.
[src:1936-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings renamed as the Boston Beaneaters and St.
[src:1936-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association and the National League, along with the Northwestern League, sign the Tripartite Agreement (also known as the National Agreement).
[src:1936-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] This agreement binds the leagues to respect each other's valid player contracts as well as increasing the size of the reserve list from 6 to 11 players.
[src:1936-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The 1883 schedule consisted of 98 games for all teams in the American Association and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:1936-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 14 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:1936-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] This format was unique to the 1883 season.
[src:1936-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Previously, the National League had played an 84-game schedule, with 12 games against each team being played, while a pre-expansion six-team American Association had played an 80-game schedule, with 16 games against each team being played.
[src:1936-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see the National League play a 112-game schedule (increase of 14 to 16 games each), while the American Association would expanded again, this time to twelve teams, for a 110-game schedule (of 10 games against each of the other eleven teams).
[src:1936-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all sixteen teams.
[src:1936-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] American Association would see its final day of the regular season on September 30 featuring four teams, while the National League would see its final day of the regular season on September 29, featuring all eight teams.
[src:1936-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] 6 tie games (1 in AA, 5 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:1936-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Louisville Eclipse and New York Metropolitans had one tie game each.
[src:1936-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues and Detroit Wolverines had three tie games each.
[src:1936-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Buffalo Bisons and Philadelphia Quakers had one tie game each.
[src:1936-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Polo Grounds, home of the New York Metropolitans and Gothams, featured two baseball fields, at the southeast and southwest of the grounds.
[src:1936-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Gothams played entirely at the southeast grounds, while the Metropolitans moved alternated.
[src:1936-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The played ten games at the southeast diamond to start the season, before moving to the southwest diamond on May 30.
[src:1936-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The southwest diamond was of worse quality than the southeast diamond, so games at the southwest diamond did not last long.
[src:1936-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] They played only ten games (aside from a one-off at the southeast diamond on June 13) before returning to the southeast diamond in July.
[src:1936-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] They did play three more games at the southwest diamond on August 30, 31, and September 4 due to scheduling conflicts with the Gothams.
[src:1936-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Following a fire and a flood of their home at Exposition Park, the Pittsburgh Alleghenys had to move into a newly built venue, a second iteration of Exposition Park, which was built immediately south.
[src:1936-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] However, after only 17 games, they played their last game there on June 9 and returned to the first Exposition Park on June 12.
[src:1936-world-series/1883-new-york-gothams-season] The **1883 New York Gothams season** was the first professional baseball season played by the team now known as the **San Francisco Giants**.
[src:1936-world-series/1883-new-york-gothams-season] The team replaced the Troy Trojans when the National League awarded its franchise rights to John B.
[src:1936-world-series/1883-new-york-gothams-season] The team went 46–50, finishing in sixth place.
[src:1936-world-series/1884-new-york-gothams-season] The **1884 New York Gothams season** was the second season of that baseball franchise, eventually known as the San Francisco Giants.
[src:1936-world-series/1884-new-york-gothams-season] The team finished in fourth place, 22 games behind the pennant-winning Providence Grays.
[src:1936-world-series/1886-new-york-giants-season] The **1886 New York Giants season** was the franchise's fourth season.
[src:1936-world-series/1886-new-york-giants-season] The team had a record of 75–44, finishing third in the National League, 12.5 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1936-world-series/1887-new-york-giants-season] The **1887 New York Giants season** was the franchise's fifth season.
[src:1936-world-series/1887-new-york-giants-season] The team finished in fourth place in the National League with a record of 68–55, 10+1⁄2 games behind the Detroit Wolverines.
[src:1936-world-series/1887-new-york-giants-season] The team amassed 415 stolen bases, the most for any team in the history of the National League.
[src:1936-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] The **1888 New York Giants season** was the franchise's sixth season.
[src:1936-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] Claiming six future Hall of Famers (Roger Connor, Mickey Welch, Buck Ewing, Tim Keefe, Jim O'Rourke, and John Montgomery Ward), the team won the National League pennant by nine games and defeated the St.
[src:1936-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] Keefe led the league in several major statistical categories, including wins, winning percentage, strikeouts, and earned run average.
[src:1936-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] The Giants beat the American Association champion St.
[src:1936-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] Louis Browns in the World Series, six games to four.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] The **1936 World Series** was the championship series in Major League Baseball for the 1936 season.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] The 33rd edition of the World Series, it matched the New York Yankees against the New York Giants, with the Yankees winning in six games to earn their fifth championship.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] The Yankees played their first World Series without Babe Ruth and their first with Joe DiMaggio, Ruth having been released by the Yankees after the 1934 season.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] He retired in 1935 as a member of the Boston Braves.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] Carl Hubbell won Game 1, allowing only one run on George Selkirk's home run and seven hits.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] After Dick Bartell's fifth inning home run off Red Ruffing tied the game, an RBI single by Gus Mancuso scoring Mel Ott, who doubled to lead off, in the sixth inning put the Giants up 2–1.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] They padded their lead in the eighth inning.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] Two singles and a walk loaded the bases before a walk to Burgess Whitehead and sacrifice fly by Travis Jackson scored a run each.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] Hubbell's two-run single capped the game's scoring.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] He pitched a perfect ninth as the Giants took a 1–0 series lead.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] The Yankees won Game 2 at the Polo Grounds by an 18–4 count, setting Series records (as of 2023) for the biggest margin of victory in a World Series game (14 runs) and the most runs scored in one game with 18.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] They loaded the bases with no outs in the first off Hal Schumacher on two singles and a walk before sacrifice flies by Lou Gehrig and Bill Dickey put them up 2–0.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] Two walks and a wild pitch by Lefty Gomez in the second inning allowed the Giants to cut the lead to 2–1, but the Yankees blew the game open in the third inning.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] A single, walk and error loaded the bases with no outs.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] Al Smith relieved Schumacher and allowed a two-run single to Gehrig and RBI single to Dickey.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] A one-out walk reloaded the bases before Tony Lazzeri's grand slam off Dick Coffman made it 9–1 Yankees.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] The Giants scored their last three runs in the fourth inning on a bases loaded walk to Dick Bartell followed by a two-run single by Bill Terry.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] The Yankees added a run in the sixth on Joe DiMaggio's sacrifice fly with two on off Frank Gabler, then loaded the bases in the seventh on a walk and two singles before Lazzeri's flyout and Gomez's groundout scored a run each.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] In the ninth, Jake Powell drew a leadoff walk off Harry Gumbert, stole second, moved to third on a groundout, and scored on Gomez's single.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] After another single, back-to-back RBI singles by Red Rolfe and DiMaggio made it 15–4 Yankees.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] One out later, Dickey's three-run home run capped the scoring.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] DiMaggio made a tremendous play in Game 2.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] With two outs in the bottom of the ninth inning, Hank Leiber drove the ball 490 feet (150 m) deep into dead center, and Joe caught the ball running up the steps of the clubhouse.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] This remarkable catch was at least 40 feet (12 m) further than Willie Mays' far more celebrated catch of Vic Wertz's drive to deep straightaway center in Game 1 of the 1954 World Series.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] After DiMaggio's game-ending grab, President Roosevelt, who was in attendance, saluted Joe for his great catch as he rode off in the presidential limousine.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] All three ninth-inning outs were made by DiMaggio.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] Yankee second baseman Tony Lazzeri became only the second player ever to hit a grand slam home run in the World Series.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] Elmer Smith of the Cleveland Indians had been the sole achiever of that feat in World Series play, doing so in Game 5 of the 1920 World Series.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] After seeing the score of this game, legendary Dodgers broadcaster Vin Scully (then 9 years old) became a Giants fan as he felt bad for the losing side.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] He credited this game as the game that made him fall in love with the game of baseball.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] Pat Malone pitched a scoreless ninth for the save.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] The Yankees struck first in the second when Jake Powell reached on an error and scored on George Selkirk's single off Carl Hubbell.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] Next inning, Frank Crosetti hit a leadoff double and scored on Red Rolfe's single, then Lou Gehrig's two-run home run gave the Yankees a 4–0 lead.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] Jimmy Ripple's RBI single in the fourth off Monte Pearson put the Giants on the board.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] Bill Terry's groundout with runners on first and third in the eighth cut the Yankees' lead to two, but they got that run back in the bottom half when Gehrig hit a leadoff double off Frank Gabler and scored on Powell's single.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] Pearson won his first World Series game (he won three more, in 1937, 1938, and 1939).
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] The Giants struck first with back-to-back leadoff doubles by Jo-Jo Moore and Dick Bartell off Red Ruffing.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] RBI singles by Jimmy Ripple and Burgess Whitehead made it 3–0 Giants.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] George Selkirk's home run off Hal Schumacher in the second put the Yankees on the board.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] Next inning, with runners on second and third, an error on Frank Crosetti's groundball allowed another run to score.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] A similar situation in the sixth on Burgess Whitehead's groundball allowed the Giants to pad their lead to 4–2, but in the bottom half, three consecutive two-out singles allowed the Yankees to tie the game.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] Bill Terry's sacrifice fly in the top of the tenth inning off Pat Malone, scoring Jo-Jo Moore, who doubled to leadoff and moved to third on a sacrifice bunt, helped the Giants win Game 5, 5–4, to extend the series to a Game Six.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] The Giants loaded the bases in the first off Lefty Gomez on a single and two walks before Mel Ott drove in two with a double, but Jake Powell's home-run after a two-out triple off Freddie Fitzsimmons tied the game in the second.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] Next inning, Lou Gehrig's sacrifice fly after two one-out singles put the Yankees up 3–2.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] They extended their lead to 5–2 in the fourth on four singles, two of which (by Gomez and Red Rolfe) scored a run each.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] Ott's home run in the fifth cut the lead to 5–3, then in the seventh, Dick Bartell hit a leadoff double and scored on Bill Terry's single to make it a one-run game.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] Tony Lazzeri's RBI single in the eighth off Slick Castleman made it 6–4 Yankees, but the Giants again cut the lead to one on Jo-Jo Moore's home run in the bottom half off Johnny Murphy.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] The Yankees, though, blew it open in the ninth.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] After two leadoff singles off Dick Coffman, an error on Bill Dickey's fielder's choice allowed one run to score.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] A walk loaded the bases before Powell drove in two more runs for the Yankees with a single.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] Harry Gumbert relieved Coffman and after a walk loaded the bases, Murphy's single, Crosetti's walk, Rolfe's groundout, and Joe DiMaggio's single scored a run each to make it 13–5 Yankees.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] It was the first time in history that a team would score seven runs in the 9th inning of a postseason game.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] No team has surpassed this mark, although five have tied it (the next one to occur after this one took place 34 years later).
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] Murphy retired the Giants in order in the bottom of the ninth to give the Yankees the championship.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] The Yankees' fifth championship tied the record at that time, which was shared by the Boston Red Sox and the Philadelphia Athletics, who also had five World Series titles.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] The Yankees also tied the American League record at that time for the most World Series appearances with eight, also shared with the Athletics.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] They broke both records the following year.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] The Giants appeared in their 11th World Series, extending the record they already held at that time, and their seventh World Series defeat also extended the record they already owned.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] DiMaggio would go on to be the only person to play on four World Championship teams in his first four years in the big leagues, the 1936–39 Yankees.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] The Yankee left fielder Jake Powell started the year with the Washington Senators before coming over in the middle of the year in a trade for Ben Chapman.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] In this Series, the unheralded Powell would lead all hitters in hits (10), batting average (.455), runs (8) and walks (4), add a home run with five runs batted in, and grab the Yankees' only stolen base.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] However, it proved to be a fleeting moment of fame for the troubled ballplayer, who gambled away the World Series check not long after before fizzling out with the Yankees by 1940, amidst controversial remarks involving him beating people as a cop to train in the offseason.
[src:1936-world-series/1936-world-series] He died in 1948 at the age of 40 after shooting himself in a police station for passing bad checks.
[src:1936-world-series/giants-season] The **1885 New York Giants season** was the franchise's third season.
[src:1936-world-series/giants-season] The team finished in second place, 2 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
